  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison arrived in Syracuse in a severe rainstorm. Garrison writes about his trip: &quot;Mr. Wise, of Auburn, accompanied me as far as Albany, and then went to the Delavan House to find lodgings for the night.&quot; Garrison waited for Samuel Joseph May, who didn&apos;t come. He finally hired a hack and was driven to Samuel Joseph May&apos;s home. Garrison arrived at Mr. May&apos;s &quot;in a state of bodily collapse, and my spirits quite flabby-dabby.&quot; Mr. May has had a bad cough for the past month. Charlotte&apos;s health is better. Garrison decided not to lecture in Erie, Pa. Garrison comments: &quot;My travelling expenses will undoubtedly make a considerable hole in my receipts. At the Pittsfield depot they charged me thirty cents for two dough-nuts and a small cup of coffee.&quot;</subfield>
